diseases.name: Maple Syrup Urine Disease
diseases.description:
• Catabolism of the branched-chain amino acids (isoleucine, leucine and valine) first produces the branched-chain α-ketoacids, which is then converted by the branched-chain α-ketoacid dehydrogenase to CoA derivatives for further catabolism.
  • Deficiencies of the branched-chain α-ketoacid dehydrogenase causes Maple Syrup Urine disease (MSUD) that is characterized by high levels of the branched-chain α-ketoacid in the blood and urine and maple syrup-like smell of the urine.
  • MSUD exhibits neurological problems and high mortality rate. Patients with it should avoid diet rich in the branched-chain amino acids or high protein contents.
